Update README to use pickFirst over exclude.

It’s good practice to include the licenses/notices in the build because those are important and most likely a part of the licenses.

Using `pickFirst` will pick only the first one, thus removing the “duplicate files....” error, while also following the licenses requirements.

Up getRelativeTimeSpanString() min resolution

Don't switch on an interval just because we're off by less than a second.

Made tests much more consistent

Basically, the left side (what the assertion should equal) is mroe hardcoded.
This means that the tests have a consistent output they should be doing.

Most of this was achieved by setting a consistent "now" time for all tests
that doesn't vary.

The only place where this wasn't done is where the output can be platform
specific, e.g. formatDateRange() isn't fully implemented in our own DateUtils
and depends on Android.

Removed "now" parameter from getRelativeTimeSpanString()

It didn't make sense that you'd need to pass in "now" when you
always want to compare the time to the current time.

By getting rid of it, it makes the API a lot easier to read/understand.

Also expanded test coverage to cover all API calls related to
getRelativeTimeSpanString()

Removed excessive parameterization of methods

Having methods that mixed ReadablePartials/ReadableInstants was a bit
overkill.  First, it cluttered up the class, making it harder to tell
what method you wanted to use.  Second, its behavior is too random.
Depending on what partials you pass in, random fields get filled in
between it and ReadableInstant it usually needs to be converted into.

By keeping everything partial or instant, we have a grounding for
comparing the parameters and keep things a bit more succinct.

Added resource_extractor.py

There are a *lot* of translations for the string files from AOSP.  This

Added ResourceZoneInfoProvider, set as default

The ResourceZoneInfoProvider acts the same as ZoneInfoProvider,
except that it loads Android resources (from the library) instead of
from the JAR.  I've also set it to be the default Provider, as the
normal ZoneInfoProvider wouldn't work anymore anyways.

Added ResUtils.getIdentifier()

So that we can convert the String-based references to raw resources
quickly and easily.

Added compiled TZ data to res/raw

I'm not a huge fan of having compiled data in the source; but
there's no other way for someone to easily check out the source and
start using it immediately otherwise right now (unless they can use
apklibs or aars, not something I want to assume at this point).

ZoneInfoCompiler now outputs Android-friendly files

It takes its paths and converts them into something that can be placed
inside of an Android resource directory.  In particular:

- It removes all directory references, replacing them with underscores.
  This makes it output to a single directory.

- It replaces some commonly seen illegal characters in TZ identifiers
  with something Android can use.

- Prefixes all files with "__tzdata_" to keep them separate from any
  other resources that someone might be using.
